<h1>LG Washer Control Board Replacement</h1>

<p>The control board is the brain of your LG washer, so when it fails you get dead panels, buttons that don't respond, or random unrelated error codes. It's also the part most often replaced by mistake, so we test the cheaper suspects first and only swap the board when it's truly the board. When it is, we install an OEM control board same-day across LA — $300–420 with a one-year warranty. Call (323) 990-7550.</p>

<h2>Signs Your Control Board Has Failed</h2>
<p>A failing board shows up as a dead display, buttons that don't respond, a cycle that won't start or stops at random, or several unrelated error codes appearing at once. Those symptoms often look like an <a href="/washer/symptoms/lg-washer-wont-turn-on/">LG washer that won't turn on</a> or an <a href="/washer/symptoms/lg-washer-not-starting/">LG washer that won't start</a> — which is exactly why the symptoms alone don't confirm the board. The same behavior can come from a door lock, a hall sensor, or a loose connector, so the board is never our first assumption.</p>

<h2>How We Replace the Control Board</h2>
<p>Our techs work the cheaper suspects first — the door lock, the hall sensor, the wiring, and the incoming power — because any of those can mimic a dead board. Only once the board is confirmed as the fault do we fit an OEM replacement, then retest every function through a cycle to make sure the machine behaves. It's about a 1–1.5 hour job.</p>

<h2>Cost of Control Board Replacement</h2>
<p>Control board replacement runs $300–420 installed, and the board itself is the bulk of that — labor is modest by comparison. The $65 diagnostic is waived when you approve the repair. For the full breakdown of where that number comes from, see our <a href="/washer/price-list/lg-washer-control-board-replacement-cost/">LG washer control board replacement cost</a> page.</p>

<h2>Why We Test First</h2>
<p>The board is the single most expensive part to replace by mistake, so confirming it before ordering one protects you from paying for a part the machine didn't need. Power surges and brownouts are a common cause of board failure, which is why a board can die suddenly on an otherwise healthy washer — if yours failed after an outage, we'll suggest a plug-in surge protector to guard the new board.</p>

<h2>OEM Parts and Warranty</h2>
<p>We fit OEM control boards, not refurbished or generic units that can carry the same fault forward, and back the work with a one-year warranty on parts and labor. There's no surcharge for same-day or weekend service.</p>

<p>Panel dead or acting erratic? Our LG Dryer Repair techs test the control path on-site across LA, Orange County, and Ventura County and quote before any work. Call (323) 990-7550; the $65 diagnostic is waived when you approve the repair.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions — LG Washer Control Board Replacement</h2>

<h3>How do I know if my LG washer control board is bad?</h3>
<p>A failing LG washer control board shows up as a dead panel, unresponsive buttons, or several unrelated error codes at once. But those same symptoms come from a door lock, hall sensor, or wiring fault too, so the symptoms alone don't confirm the board.</p>

<h3>How much does LG washer control board replacement cost?</h3>
<p>Control board replacement runs $300–420 installed with an OEM board, most of which is the part itself. The $65 diagnostic is waived when you approve the repair, and the work carries a one-year warranty. We're licensed with the Bureau of Household Goods and Services (#49573).</p>

<h3>Why do you test other parts before replacing the control board?</h3>
<p>Because the board is the most expensive part to replace by mistake. A dead panel or stuck cycle is often a door lock, hall sensor, or loose connector — far cheaper fixes — so we confirm those aren't the cause before quoting a board.</p>

<h3>What causes an LG washer control board to fail?</h3>
<p>Power surges and brownouts are the most common cause, which is why a board can die suddenly on an otherwise healthy washer. Age and moisture also play a part. If yours failed after an outage, a plug-in surge protector is cheap insurance for the new board.</p>

<h3>Is replacing the control board worth it or should I replace the washer?</h3>
<p>On a newer LG washer, yes — $300–420 versus $800–1,500 for a new machine. On an older washer with other parts failing, a new board may not be the smartest spend, and we'll give you an honest read before you commit.</p>

